being these liaisons and reps for SoQure, and then what happens is, like I mentioned before,

00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:47.880
our clients will call our API, and they will get model scores back as a result, and then all of

00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:54.520
that data lands in our databases so that we have visibility into what's actually happening with our

00:25:54.520 --> 00:26:03.079
products, and from there, once that data is in our databases, our data scientists can publish

00:26:03.079 --> 00:26:10.439
a monitor or a report that ingests that data and displays, you know, some of the stats,

00:26:10.439 --> 00:26:16.599
some of the health of our business. So, in broad terms, that's kind of how we think about it,

00:26:16.599 --> 00:26:20.199
and that's the framework we're going to use for thinking about scaling going forward here.

00:26:20.199 --> 00:26:27.239
So, once those monitors are deployed, our account managers can view these reports,

00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:32.760
these monitors might fire alerts back to our account managers, and then based on that information,

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:36.439
our account managers can decide whether and how to communicate back to our clients

00:26:36.439 --> 00:26:37.959
what's happening with our products.

00:26:37.959 --> 00:26:47.479
Okay. So, let's think about the scaling process and sort of the level one. The first step you

00:26:47.479 --> 00:26:54.280
might take in monitoring a client or monitoring a model is just to create something bespoke or just

00:26:54.280 --> 00:27:02.920
to create a custom monitor for every individual client or every individual need. When you create

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:08.760
a custom monitor for every individual client or every individual need, when you're small,

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:12.599
it kind of makes sense to start out that way because, you know, maybe you only have a few

00:27:12.599 --> 00:27:17.640
