00:27:46.359 --> 00:27:53.800
can receive alerts. Okay. Time goes on, and now we acquire some new customers, and now we have

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:59.560
Gringotts Bank, and now we also have Dunder Mifflin. These are our new clients. So, our account

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:04.839
managers say, okay, we're going to, you know, look at some specific model outputs for these clients,

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:10.280
and so data science goes and publishes custom reports for those clients as well.

00:28:12.280 --> 00:28:18.599
So, again, this is still sort of the prototyping phase, figuring out, you know, which metrics are

00:28:18.599 --> 00:28:24.280
actually useful, and this is a good place to start. The trouble here is that this can be very

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:28.680
time-consuming. Maybe every monitor looks different, so, you know, it's a little bit

00:28:30.439 --> 00:28:36.040
hard to go from one monitor to the other and understand sort of what's happening in each one.

00:28:36.040 --> 00:28:43.719
There's a little bit of, like, cognitive overhead there. So, as time goes on, you will want to

00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:50.439
begin to standardize via template. Sorry, this should be level two. So, in level two, you're

00:28:50.439 --> 00:28:56.599
going to be thinking about, can we monitor some key inputs and model scores across all the clients?

00:28:56.599 --> 00:29:00.760
So, maybe there are some clients that require a little bit of extra customization, and that's

00:29:00.760 --> 00:29:07.479
totally fine, but can we figure out maybe a templated solution where, for most of our clients,

00:29:07.479 --> 00:29:12.439
we just know these are the inputs we care about, and these are the outputs we care about?

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:17.479
So, customization kind of becomes secondary, and you just want that consistency,

00:29:18.280 --> 00:29:20.119
those standardized reporting practices.

00:29:22.839 --> 00:29:28.359
So, what might that look like? Data Science might decide to create a report template,

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:35.959
and this is how we did it for a while as well, and this template is going to contain a lot of

00:29:37.319 --> 00:29:41.400
logic in the body of that report, and all that logic is going to be essentially the same for each

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:51.800
client, but what you'll do is you can go in in each report and say, you know, this report is for

00:29:53.560 --> 00:29:59.959
Willy Wonka, or this report is for Gringotts, or whoever it is, and then the downstream logic

00:29:59.959 --> 00:30:05.640
can then go and grab the data specific to those clients, and then each report can be

00:30:06.599 --> 00:30:13.160
a templated version of this standard monitoring framework, except it's client-specific.

00:30:15.239 --> 00:30:19.640
So, in our case at SoQure, what we did is we created a template, and then we

00:30:21.959 --> 00:30:24.920
customized each template and deployed into a GitLab repo,

00:30:26.920 --> 00:30:31.479
and so now we have a whole bunch of monitors, each one showing the same kinds of things,

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:35.560
but each one for a different client, and then we can use what's called this Git-backed

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:41.640
deployment process in RStudio Connect to actually pull those reports straight into Connect,

00:30:41.640 --> 00:30:46.520
which is super nice, because if you wanted to go in later and update one of these templates,

00:30:46.520 --> 00:30:52.680
maybe you wanted to tweak a threshold value for one of your alerts, you could do that,

00:30:52.680 --> 00:30:57.880
you could push those changes to GitLab, and then maybe the next day RStudio Connect is going to

00:30:57.880 --> 00:31:02.599
go grab those changes and then publish those reports on Connect.

00:31:06.839 --> 00:31:12.040
So, this was really helpful. This is a really nice system for a while. The problem here is

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:16.119
that this is a little bit time-consuming, and there's a multi-step deployment process

00:31:16.119 --> 00:31:19.640
that can be a little bit cumbersome, again, as you continue to scale up,

00:31:20.280 --> 00:31:26.760
which is what happened to us. So, time goes by, and all of a sudden we have a lot more clients,

00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:32.439
