So, broadly speaking, in this auto-monitor package, and I'll talk more about these specifics

00:32:09.959 --> 00:32:14.280
later, but broadly speaking, there's this deploy function, and deploy just says,

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:22.680
give me your account name and give me your configuration, and I will put together a

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:26.359
template and a configuration, and I will create a monitor, and I will deploy that.

00:32:27.400 --> 00:32:31.560
So, this template can live inside your package, so you just throw it in the

00:32:32.280 --> 00:32:38.280
int directory, and then this configuration is just going to be a list of client-specific details,

00:32:38.359 --> 00:32:39.800
monitoring thresholds, and so forth.

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:49.400
Also, inside this auto-monitor package are just your standard monitoring functions,

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:55.079
and so those are what get used inside your template, and you can use – and this is,

00:32:55.079 --> 00:32:58.599
like, super cool – you can use the RSConnect package and the Connect API

00:32:59.719 --> 00:33:04.520
package to add viewer permissions. You can set your refresh schedule.

00:33:04.520 --> 00:33:09.560
You can tag deployed content so it's easy to find. You can do all these really cool things

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:14.920
programmatically, so you don't have to deploy a report and then go to Connect

00:33:14.920 --> 00:33:18.760
and configure everything manually. You can do all of this programmatically from R.

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:27.319
So, now, with auto-monitor, we can just say, I want to deploy. I'm going to deploy for,

00:33:28.119 --> 00:33:33.160
you know, this specific client. Maybe you have a set of config defaults,

00:33:33.719 --> 00:33:38.040
so you don't have to worry about that either. You can just programmatically run through all

00:33:38.040 --> 00:33:42.040
