01:09:58.279 --> 01:10:03.959
if you parameterize your R markdown, that just means your YAML header is given a set of

01:10:03.959 --> 01:10:09.160
configurable parameters, which then you can pass downstream to all of your R code.

01:10:10.359 --> 01:10:13.319
So that's definitely an option. I think

01:10:16.359 --> 01:10:21.160
there are some limitations with how we're doing it here. So I think one limitation is

01:10:21.799 --> 01:10:28.520
a parameterized report is like one single monolithic piece of content

01:10:29.160 --> 01:10:35.399
on Connect. But I don't believe that you can very easily control the access

01:10:36.120 --> 01:10:41.799
and the scheduling for each individual variant that you render. So what you can do on Connect

01:10:41.799 --> 01:10:47.319
is once you deploy that parameterized piece of content, you then can open this nice sidebar,

01:10:47.319 --> 01:10:52.839
and it gives you a way to change all of the input parameters to those reports. So you want

01:10:52.839 --> 01:10:57.000
to change the account ID, you want to change the reporting window, you want to change the thresholds,

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:01.879
